<setup>
  <function name="f">2^x</function>
  <derivative name="fP">$f</derivative>
  <function name="g" styleNumber="3">ln(x)/(ln(2))</function>
  <derivative name="gP">$g</derivative>

  <label name="flabel" anchor="(2.25,9.5)"><m>y=f(x)</m></label>
  <label name="glabel" anchor="(9.25, 3.65)"><m>y=g(x)</m></label>
  
  <number name="a">1</number>
  <number name="b">2</number>
  <number name="c">3</number>

  <number name="p">2</number>
  <number name="q">4</number>
  <number name="r">8</number> 
  
  <lineSegment name="segmentA" endpoints="($a - 0.5,$$f($a) + $$fP($a)(-0.5)) ($a + 0.5,$$f($a) + $$fP($a)(+0.5))" styleNumber="2" />
  <point name="A"  styleNumber="2" draggable="false" >($a, $$f($a))</point>
  <label name="Alabel" anchor="(1.75,1.75)"><m>A (2,1)</m></label>
  
  <lineSegment name="segmentB" endpoints="($b - 0.35,$$f($b) + $$fP($b)(-0.35)) ($b + 0.35,$$f($b) + $$fP($b)(+0.35))" styleNumber="2" />
  <point name="B"  styleNumber="2" draggable="false" >($b, $$f($b))</point>
  <label name="Blabel" anchor="(2.75,3.75)"><m>B (2,4)</m></label>
  
  <lineSegment name="segmentC" endpoints="($c - 0.25,$$f($c) + $$fP($c)(-0.25)) ($c + 0.25,$$f($c) + $$fP($c)(+0.25))" styleNumber="2" />
  <point name="C"  styleNumber="2" draggable="false" >($c, $$f($c))</point>
  <label name="Clabel" anchor="(3.75,7.75)"><m>C (3,8)</m></label>
  
  <lineSegment name="segmentD" endpoints="($p - 0.75,$$g($p) + $$gP($p)(-0.75)) ($p + 0.75,$$g($p) + $$gP($p)(+0.75))" styleNumber="4" />
  <point name="D"  styleNumber="4" draggable="false" >($p, $$g($p))</point>
  <label name="Dlabel" anchor="(2.25,0.75)"><m>P</m></label>
  
  <lineSegment name="segmentE" endpoints="($q - 0.75,$$g($q) + $$gP($q)(-0.75)) ($q + 0.75,$$g($q) + $$gP($q)(+0.75))" styleNumber="4" />
  <point name="E"  styleNumber="4" draggable="false" >($q, $$g($q))</point>
  <label name="Elabel" anchor="(4.25,1.75)"><m>Q</m></label>

  <lineSegment name="segmentF" endpoints="($r - 0.75,$$g($r) + $$gP($r)(-0.75)) ($r + 0.75,$$g($r) + $$gP($r)(+0.75))" styleNumber="4" />
  <point name="F"  styleNumber="4" draggable="false" >($r, $$g($r))</point>
  <label name="Flabel" anchor="(8.25,2.75)"><m>R</m></label>
  
</setup>

<p>
  Consider the function <m>f(x) = 2^x</m>, which is invertible since <m>2^x</m> is always increasing.  A plot of <m>f</m> along with its inverse <m>g</m> is shown below.
</p>  

<graph xMin="-1" xMax="10" yMin="-1" yMax="10" grid="true" showNavigation="false" fixAxes="true">
  $f
  $flabel
  $g
  $glabel
  
  $segmentA
  $A
  $Alabel
  
  $segmentB
  $B
  $Blabel
  
  $segmentC
  $C
  $Clabel

  $segmentD
  $D
  $Dlabel

  $segmentE
  $E
  $Elabel  

  $segmentF
  $F
  $Flabel  
  
</graph>  

<p>
  <ol marker="a.">
    <li>
      <p>
        To begin, determine the derivative of <m>f(x)</m>. 
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>f'(x) = </m><answer><award>$fP</award></answer>
      </p>  
    </li>  
    <li>
      <p>
        At each of the points <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>, determine the slope of each of the respective tangent lines to <m>y = f(x)</m>.  Report each of your results to an accuracy of at least <m>0.01</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The slope of the tangent line to <m>y = f(x)</m> at <m>A</m> is <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award>$$fP($a)</award></answer>.
      </p>   
      <p>
        The slope of the tangent line to <m>y = f(x)</m> at <m>B</m> is <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award>$$fP($b)</award></answer>.
      </p>   
      <p>
        The slope of the tangent line to <m>y = f(x)</m> at <m>C</m> is <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award>$$fP($c)</award></answer>.
      </p> 
    </li>  
    <li>
      <p>
        Recall that if <m>(a,b)</m> is a point that lies on the graph of <m>y = f(x)</m>, then the point <m>(b,a)</m> lies on the graph of its inverse, <m>y = g(x)</m>.  State the coordinates of each of the points <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m>, writing each as an ordered pair.
      </p>  
      <p>
        <m>P = </m><answer><award>($p, $$g($p))</award></answer>
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>Q = </m><answer><award>($q, $$g($q))</award></answer>
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>R = </m><answer><award>($r, $$g($r))</award></answer>
      </p>
    </li>  
    <li>
      <p>
        At each of the points <m>D</m>, <m>E</m>, and <m>F</m>, determine the slope of each of the respective tangent lines to <m>y = g(x)</m>.  Report each of your results to an accuracy of at least <m>0.01</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The slope of the tangent line to <m>y = g(x)</m> at <m>D</m> is <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award>$$gP($p)</award></answer>.
      </p>   
      <p>
        The slope of the tangent line to <m>y = g(x)</m> at <m>E</m> is <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award>$$gP($q)</award></answer>.
      </p>   
      <p>
        The slope of the tangent line to <m>y = g(x)</m> at <m>F</m> is <answer allowedErrorInNumbers="0.01" allowedErrorIsAbsolute><award>$$gP($r)</award></answer>.
      </p> 
    </li>    
    <li>
      <p>
        An important relationship between the slope of the tangent line to <m>y = f(x)</m> at <m>A</m> and the corresponding slope of the tangent line to <m>y = g(x)</m> at <m>E</m> is that these two slopes are <answer>
                <choiceInput inline>
                  <choice>?</choice>
                  <choice>opposites</choice>
                  <choice credit="1">reciprocals</choice>
                  <choice>equal</choice>
                </choiceInput>  
              </answer>.  
      </p>  
    </li>  
  </ol>

</p>  
